ely hypothetical, given that in more\nrecent history where we have better documentation it is very common for groups\nmany would classify as bandits claiming to fight for some cause or other, e.g.\npost ACW bandits claiming to be carrying the torch of the confederacy, or more\nexamples claiming to espouse Marxism, Islamic fundamentalism, etc. The fact\nthat those groups are better documented also lets us have debates about their\nsincerity, but by the same token sincerity is hard to assess in an ancient\nRoman context!\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n        1. Arilou says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 7:28 pm\n\nI don\u2019t think the borders being difficult to define really undercuts the\ngeneral category though. Yeah, sometimes government and banditry can be hard\nto separate, but in other cases they aren\u2019t.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n          1. topherbrennan says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 8:08 pm\n\nThis reads a bit like it was intended as a response to ad9 that got posted\nunder my comment by accident. If it was intentional, my point was not even\nabout government vs. banditry but ideologically motivated guerrillas vs.\nbanditry, in a context where we only know about them through their wealthy,\nelite enemies.\n\nLoading...\n\n        2. aldarion76 says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 12:21 pm\n\nApuleius\u2019 Golden Ass contains a good and detailed description of a band of\npeople in Thrace and Greece who assault civilians for entirely material\nreasons. Apuleius was of course a cultured man, but I don\u2019t see why one would\ndoubt there were bandits of exactly the type he described in such detail.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      2. ad9 says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 6:02 pm\n\nTo quote the late, great, Terry Pratchett:\n\n\u201cGenua had once controlled the river mouth and taxed its traffic in a way that\ncouldn\u2019t be called piracy because it was done by the city government\u201d\n\nAs a number of people have observed, there can be no clear distinction between\nbanditry and gov