iryW says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 3:53 am\n\nAn army campaigns in pursuit of a political objectives and political results\nwill make them start or stop campaigning. An \u201cactual\u201d bandit may respond to\nthe political situation (banditry gets a lot more dangerous in times of peace)\nbut they aren\u2019t motivated by political concerns.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    3. Dinwar says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 9:23 am\n\nI don\u2019t think there IS a hard distinction between the two. Look at Robin\nHood\u2013starts out as landed nobility, ends up a bandit, becomes strong enough to\nactually have a go at becoming landed nobility again.\n\nThat said, I think it\u2019s fair to differentiate \u201creal\u201d banditry from enemy\nmilitary action. There were highway robbers, thugs, and criminals throughout\nhistory. They may or may not have delusions of grandeur, but from the\nperspective of the state they still represent a fundamentally different\nproblem from an enemy nation. Bandits are a threat to your INTERNAL stability\nand structures, and need to be dealt with as a matter of internal law. Enemy\narmies, even when they behave irregularly, are EXTERNAL threats, and you can\u2019t\nreally claim to have any authority over them. Negotiating with them is also\nnot really an option. A Roman statesman can negotiate with a Germanic tribe to\nend a war and everyone thinks he\u2019s achieved a great victory. The same\nstatesman negotiating with a group of bandits is considered weak (though\npirates seem to follow different rules; see the Lioness of Brittany and a\nChinese example who\u2019s name I can\u2019t remember).\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    4. Moon Moth says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 6:57 pm\n\nI think an underappreciated distinction is whether the group committing\nbanditry (or theft, or terrorism, or whatever) answers to some central\nauthority that can be negotiated with. There may not be any practical\ndistinction, for the victim, between pirates and privateers. But if you can\nnegotiate with a government to call off their privateers, the difference\nbecomes clear.\n\nIt\u2019s a fuzzy boundary, certainly. On one hand, \u201cpirate kings\u201d and organized\ncrime would cross over into the category of governments, but on the other\nhand, anarcho-libertarians might fall out of the category of governments.\n\nOn a touchier subject, as I see it Hamas currently seems able to call for\nshort truces with Israel. Since they don\u2019t have direct control over the\nactions of their armed populace, they\u2019re doing this through a sort of moral\nlegitimacy. But if they ever make an unfavorable peace with Israel, that would\ncost them their legitimacy, and therefore the peace would collapse instantly.\nAnd they\u2019ve even encouraged the factors that led to this, as a sort of game-\ntheoretic pre-committment. We can see similar trends at work in American\npolitics, where the encouragement of extremism prevents compromise, and stops\nthe party from negotiating successfully.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  6. cptbutton says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 1:45 pm\n\nTypo: \u201chard day\u2019s worth of resting\u201d ITYM \u201chard day\u2019s work of resting\u201d\n\nOf course, now I have a Beatles earworm running in my head. We will see if it\ncan overpower \u201cFlower of Hell.\u201d\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  7. Eric Monkman says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 1:55 pm\n\nWhat does \u201cLate Classical\u201d mean in the roundtable title? I would have thought\nthe late Classical period would be around the time of the slow fall of the\nWestern Roman Empire (maybe beginning with the Dominate?). This would be a\nfair time after the Hellenistic monarchies.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    1. Jaojao says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 2:07 pm\n\nWhen it comes to the history of Greece, \u201cClassical\u201d is usually in between the\nArchaic and Hellenistic periods; essentially from the Persian Wars to\nAlexander the Great. I would suppose \u201cLate Classical\u201d to be the 300s 