re than a few hundred\nyears. Suppose your medieval polity\u2019s army consists of a militia drawn from\nall reasonably prosperous households. Naturally, if you lose a battle, many of\nthose militiamen go home. Have your forces \u201cmelted away into the civilian\npopulation?\u201d They literally were the civilian population; they just picked up\nweapons to fight a battle.\n\nThe modern norm for warfare is that armies have extreme regimentation, live\napart from the general population in distinctive uniforms, and have a clear\nconcept of themselves as \u201csoldiers\u201d who are not \u201ccivilians.\u201d Those\ndistinctions and conditions would look blurrier in earlier times.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. Civile Bellum says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 11:43 am\n\nYes/no ; we see distinctions made for soldiers in a state of war going back to\nthe Ancient era.\n\nNote that the distinction is essentially, incidental. That is, it would apply\nper example or incident instead of a people or a even a given group of\nsoldiers. The exacty same people might gather into a formal army and fight at\none point, or carry out annual cattle raids or something once or twice per\nyear.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  15. Skinner_Was_Right says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 4:59 pm\n\n> And that problem is made harder by a consistent rhetoric[al] turn in a lot\n> of our sources, which of course tend to be written by the well-funded\n> political and media institutions of these modern Great Powers: the\n> rhetorical turn to represent any resistance or opposition [from] anything\n> that isn\u2019t a peer Great Power as just \u2018terrorism\u2019. You can see the\n> propaganda value of this as such a label inherently delegitimizes what might\n> be popular movements by re-classifying something like resistance simply as\n> \u2018crime\u2019 (though we should be quick to note that there is plenty of actual\n> terrorism in modern warfare as well!). But I think it was also often a\n> sincere (but motivate