lict terror on a\ncivilian populace). Strategic bombing can also be done in order to inflict\nmaterial damage on the enemy\u2019s ability to make war, by destroying factories.\n\nIn practice the line between the two was very much blurred, especially with\nsuch rationalizations as burning down entire residential neighborhoods with\nincendiary bombs in order to interfere with enemy war production by killing or\ndisplacing the factory workers.\n\nLoading...\n\n      3. Jack says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 6:39 am\n\n> I think terrorism as a tactic can be usefully defined\n\nPerhaps once upon a time; nowadays the word is most-often used to refer to\n\u201cgroup we want to destroy\u201d. Putin describes Ukrainian attacks on Russian\nterritory as \u201cterrorism\u201d. Netanyahu describes Hamas as \u201cterrorists\u201d, at the\nsame time as describing his actions in Gaza as a \u201cwar\u201d.\n\nThe definition you\u2019ve offered accurately describes the kinds of actions the\nPLO or the IRA used to undertake in the 1970s.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n        1. Roxana says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 10:37 am\n\nThe definition of terrorism is very simple; attacks on soft targets, chiefly\nwomen and children to creat fear and intimidate. The October 7th attack on\nIsraeli communities is a fine example of that definition\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      4. Roxana says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 10:39 am\n\nI agree with you.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      5. Skinner_Was_Right says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 7:08 pm\n\nI mean, one could legitimately quibble with nearly every aspect of that\ndefinition: terroristic violence doesn\u2019t inherently have to be indiscriminate\n(e.g. the 9/11 attackers striking at the most iconic symbolic edifices of U.S.\neconomic and military power), the attacks don\u2019t inherently have to be against\na civilian target (e.g. the Pentagon on 9/11), and the perpetrators don\u2019t\ninherently have to be lacking in conventional military power (e.g. Hezbollah\ndid reaso