\ndirect administration of territory. This, in turn, is a combination of\nuncertainty about what to administer (whereas Russia straightforwardly aims at\nannexing Ukrainian areas it controls) and asymmetric warfare affecting both\nbelligerents rather than just one.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  17. Bosh says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 6:32 pm\n\n\u201cto a more sophisticated social/cultural contextualization (\u2018actually, the\nrivet-count of a T-34 matters less than these other social factors...\u2019)\u201d\n\nThose social factors are important, but I\u2019ve seen professional historians be\nso contemptuous of things like T-34 rivet counts that they make some howling\nerrors. I\u2019m a beer nerd and I\u2019ve had to get the mods to erase posts by\nprofessional historians on r/AskHistorians for posting absolute nonsense of\nthe history of beer (for example, that German beer tastes the same today as it\ndid 200 years ago) and I\u2019ve listened to a podcast interview by a historian who\nwrote an ENTIRE BOOK about the social factors of beer production who admitted\nduring the interview that they knew absolutely nothing about how to actually\nproduce beer and never bothered to educate themselves about that.\n\nI don\u2019t know much about the technical details of farming, sailing, textile\nproduction, etc. etc. but if historians are making massive technical errors\nabout the one subject I know well enough to fact check them, then how many\nother technical errors about things I don\u2019t know well am I swallowing\nunknowingly when I read stuff written by professional historians? This doesn\u2019t\napply to the Pedant of course, as evidenced by the How They Made It series, he\nknows the technical details damn well.\n\nOf course social factors are generally more important, but if you\u2019re writing\nprofessionally about the T-34 you should damn well know how many rivets it\nhas.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    1. Bret Devereaux says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 8:56 pm\n\nAbsolutely that\u2019s a problem. I have an entire chapter in my book project\ndedicated to questions about how the things I am discussing were produced,\nbefore I then move to the social factors behind their production. I was once\nfloored to find out that another academic who was working on medieval military\nmasculinity had little to no sense of how a knight might be equipped or fight.\nI think a firm grounding in the realia of one\u2019s period is essential.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. Bosh says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 11:43 pm\n\nYes, I like your approach very much. Have talked with a professional historian\non r/AskHistorians where they were openly contemptuous of technical details\nsaying, to paraphrase, \u201camateurs get hung up on the technical details but we\nprofessionals have more serious things to worry about\u201d which just left me a\nbit gobsmacked (kind of like the psychologist who told me that a lot of people\nin the field still take Jung seriously, I thought his ideas were seriously\noutdated...). I can understand your eyes glazing over a bit when obsessives go\non endlessly about all of the slightly different versions of WW II firearms or\nwhat have you but I agree strongly that the kind of grounding you\u2019re talking\nabout is essential. You get historians who seem to think textual analysis is\nthe end all and be all of the field which just makes my brain hurt.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n        1. AiryW says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 4:35 am\n\nTo be fair the rivet counters can definitely fall into extreme McNamara\nfallacies. I think 3 inch vs 3.5 inch tank cannons in WWII is a classic\nexample. Armchair historians spent decades hyping up easily quantifiable\nfactors while missing the less obvious factors (ergonomics is literally a\nmatter of life and death!) that the experts (who had experienced this stuff\nfirst hand) cared about.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n          1. Bosh says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 5:38 am\n\nRight, people obsessed with those metrics can get exceptionally tedious and\noften lose sight of the big picture. Personally my eyes just glaze over when\npeople start going on about WW II weapon stats (except for really exceptional\nthings like the horrible initial design of American torpedoes in WW II). But\nif you\u2019re a professional historian you really should know what they\u2019re talking\nabout so you can avoid falling down the same rabbit holes yourself and to be\nable to put those metrics into the proper context.\n\nThe stuff I\u2019ve noticed with historians goofing about details of beer\nproduction isn\u2019t not caring about metrics, it\u2019s more not knowing what makes\ntank cannons go boom. Really surface level stuff you could get off of\nWikipedia articles.\n\nNot all historians are like this of course. I listen to a lot of history\npodcasts and I came across one interview where the historian was talking about\ntracing where in neolithic China people used malted vs. unmalted grains to\nmake alcohol by analyzing residue on pot shards, which was fascinating (she\nseemed to really know her shit) but a depressing number of historians...just\ndon\u2019t seem to bother learning even the basics of the technical details of the\nstuff they\u2019re analyzing the socio-economic implications of.\n\nLoading...\n\n  18. Arilou says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 7:32 pm\n\nI always remember some talk about how Honour is one of the hardest concepts\nfor modern westerners (but not neccessarily others) to really grasp. (along\nwith, in some sense, non-christian religiosity) in that it is often too easy\ntoa ssume that the talk of honour is *just* cynical posturing for advantage,\nwhen it is clear that at least some people *absolutely believed*, and even\nthat it affects policy in a lot of cases.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    1. Bullseye says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 9:17 pm\n\nWhich definition of honor do you mean? The older meaning, which is about\npeople actually honoring you? Or the newer one, which is about being honest\nand having personal integrity, regardless of whether other people recognize\nit?\n\nI don\u2019t think either one is foreign to modern westerners, or anyone else.\nEveryone wants respect, even if how you get respect and what it looks like\nvary from one culture to the next. And every culture teaches its members some\nform of honesty and loyalty, even if the form that takes varies.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. The original Mr. X says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 9:56 am\n\nThis doesn\u2019t really rebut the point: the reason why honour is one of the\nhardest points to grasp is precisely because \u201chow you get respect and what it\nlooks like\u201d varies so much between ancient Rome or medieval Europe and the\nmodern West.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    2. NVA says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 9:51 pm\n\nI think the \u201cadvantage\u201d is the part of honour that people believe in, and\naffects policy, not the \u201ccynical posturing\u201d part. For example people in feudal\nsocieties fought \u201chonorably\u201d because they were the ruling class and they\ndidn\u2019t want to escalate conflicts between themselves. When people fight for\ntheir survival, however, \u201chonor\u201d goes out of the window.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    3. Bosh says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 2:08 am\n\nI think it\u2019s a general human trend to underestimate the extent to which people\nbelieve their own propaganda. You can see plenty of that in modern politics.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. Mary Catelli says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 9:03 pm\n\nAnd even think it\u2019s belief in the propaganda rather than beliefs, which you\nmight try to propagate.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    4. The original Mr. X says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 9:43 am\n\nOne might point out that talking of honour as a kind of \u201ccynical posturing for\nadvantage\u201d only works when you can portray your talk as sincere, which in turn\ncan only be done in a society where most people *actually do believe in the\nconcept of honour*.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. Moon Moth says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 1:56 pm\n\nI don\u2019t understand. I\u2019ve heard plenty about honour being \u201ccynical posturing\nfor advantage\u201d, but I don\u2019t think of modern educated left-leaning American\nsociety as being a place where \u201cmost people *actually do believe in the\nconcept of honour*\u201d. What am I missing?\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n        1. cptbutton says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 2:20 pm\n\nThey believe in honour, but don\u2019t use that word, it is \u201csincereity\u201d or\n\u201cintegrity\u201d or something. Because \u201chonor\u201d has been taken over by the macho\nbrutality fans as the reason to do horrible things to people. Just another\ncase of slash-and-burn linguistics.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n        2. The original Mr. X says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 2:32 pm\n\nBy \u201ctalking of honour as a kind of \u201ccynical posturing for advantage\u201d\u201d I meant\n\u201ctalking about honour as a cynical means of gaining your own advantage\u201d,\nrather than \u201csaying that honour is a kind of cynical posturing for advantage\u201d.\nApologies if that was unclear. Very few people nowadays talk about honour,\nprecisely because most people in modern educated left-leaning American society\ndon\u2019t believe in the concept.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n          1. Moon Moth says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 6:40 pm\n\nAh, OK. You\u2019re saying that you can\u2019t destructively exploit the commons for\nprivate advantage, if there aren\u2019t any commons left, and since we don\u2019t have\nany commons left, no one\u2019s destructively exploiting them. But to go back to\nthe original comment, destructively exploiting commons only works if there are\nstill some commons left, so we should expect to see the former only in places\nthat still have the latter. Makes sense, thanks!\n\nLoading...\n\n  19. Moon Moth says:\n\nApril 12, 2024 at 7:43 pm\n\nThis is the cutest cat picture of Ollie and/or Percy, at least that I can\nrecall.\n\nAnybody have links to a cuter one?\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    1. Roxana says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 10:28 am\n\nAll their pictures are adorable but this on is special.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. Moon Moth says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 6:59 pm\n\nI love it when black cats curl up in sunlight, and we can see their actual\ncoloring peek out.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  20. ey81 says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 10:00 am\n\nShouldn\u2019t that second use of \u201chetaira\u201d be, depending on your preferences in\ntranscription, either \u201chetairae\u201d or \u201chetairai\u201d?\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  21. Roxana says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 10:24 am\n\nThere is a persistent tendency to glamourize heteira as \u2018independent women\u2019\nwhen they were as totally dependent on men as conventional citizen and metic\nwomen with none of the security and support of social norms. A very few\nmanaged to make large fortunes but the majority would have loved more hand to\nmouth and sunk lower in the hierarchy of sex workers as they aged and lost\ntheir attractions to men. It annoys me.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  22. AJS says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 11:27 am\n\nI wonder if labeling raids, foraging, &c as \u201cbanditry\u201d also reflects the shame\nthat \u201csophisticated\u201d empires often seem to feel about resorting to those\ntactics. Like, the Romans used raiding, scorched earth, &c quite effectively\nagainst Hannibal (as did the Russian Empire against Napoleon, the emus against\nAustralia, & s\u00f3 forth). But you get a sense that they wished they didn\u2019t need\nto engage in such \u201cdishonorable\u201d tactics, which is why the Romans struggled to\ncommit to Fabius\u2019s strategy, & the Russians fought a probably-unnecessary meat\ngrinder battle at Borodino (the emus committed to it pretty early, tho).\nPerhaps labeling all this \u201cbanditry\u201d is also overcompensation by empires that\nreally, really wish they didn\u2019t have to do this\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n    1. ad9 says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 7:19 pm\n\nCivilized states disliked scorched earth tactics when, as in your examples,\nthey required scorching their own earth. Scorching the enemies earth was\ngenerally a lot more popular.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n      1. AJS says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 10:25 pm\n\nalso true!\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  23. georgemenz says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 1:17 pm\n\nPopping up here to say that Steven Attewell, through whom I discovered this\nblog, passed away earlier this week. My thoughts with his family and friends.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n  24. Constance Sublette says:\n\nApril 13, 2024 at 8:08 pm\n\nIn the later medieval eras and the Renaissance eras many were bandits, were\nmercenaries, were soldiers, all three, though maybe, not always, at the same\ntime. It was so common to slide from one designation by whichever top power\nthere was, to another, depending on whether one\u2019s group was winning or losing,\nor just had the bad luck to run out of supplies.\n\nLoading...\n\nReply\n\n### Leave a ReplyCancel reply\n\nUpdates every Friday!\n\nYou can support this project via Patreon, and by spreading the word!\n\n# Recent Posts\n\n  * Fireside Friday, April 12, 2024\n  * Collections: Phalanx\u2019s Twilight, Legion\u2019s Triumph, Part IVb: Antiochus III\n  * Fireside Friday, March 29, 2024 (On Roman Values)\n  * Fireside Friday, March 22, 2024\n  * Collections: Phalanx\u2019s Twilight, Legion\u2019s Triumph, Part IVa: Philip V\n  * Collections: Phalanx\u2019s Twilight, Legion\u2019s Triumph, Part IIIb: Pyrrhus\n\n# Questions? Requests?\n\nHave a topic you want me to post about? A question on a post? Do you want to\nscream incoherently into the endless void that is the internet?\n\nThe best place to find me is on twitter @BretDevereaux Following me on Twitter\nis the best way to be informed of new posts as they appear.\n\n# Tags\n\nAcademia Ancient Armor Artillery Broader Medi